{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-02-13T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Before bridges, rivers set the pace of travel. Now, with bridges, people do. That shift explains why cross-border links like the Third Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge connecting Laos and Thailand matter. Bridges come in many forms, each built to meet a specific challenge. Arch bridges manage compression, suspension bridges span long distances and concrete box-girder bridges prioritise stability and load efficiency. This bridge uses the box-girder design, making it a practical choice for crossing the wide, fast-moving Mekong River.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.FriendshipBridge_ROW0019277166_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.FriendshipBridge_ROW0019277166_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Third Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge connecting Laos and Thailand","Copyright":"© chaiyut samsuk/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260213_FriendshipBridge\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Third+Thai+Lao+Friendship+Bridge&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260213_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260213_FriendshipBridge"},"Ssd":"20260213","Name":"FriendshipBridge","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0019277166","FullDateString":"13. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"When romance calls, this bird lifts one bright blue foot, then the other, like it's auditioning for a talent show with very strict colour rules. Not metaphorically. Literally. Meet the blue-footed booby. Widely associated with the Galápagos Islands, these seabirds range across the eastern tropical Pacific.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DarwinBooby_ROW9751594098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DarwinBooby_ROW9751594098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Blue-footed booby, Galápagos Islands, Ecuador","Copyright":"© Karine Aigner/TANDEM Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260212_DarwinBooby\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Blue+footed+booby&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260212_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260212_DarwinBooby"},"Ssd":"20260212","Name":"DarwinBooby","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9751594098","FullDateString":"12. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Death Valley National Park challenges first impressions. Spanning more than 1.34 million hectares across California and Nevada in the United States, it is the largest national park in the contiguous United States. Across this vast expanse, salt flats, volcanic hills, sweeping sand dunes and distant snowcapped peaks create a landscape shaped by time and extremes. From the soaring heights of Telescope Peak, which rises over 3,300 metres above the desert floor, to the depths of Badwater Basin, 86 metres below sea level, the park is a study in contrasts.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BadwaterFlats_ROW9539566313_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BadwaterFlats_ROW9539566313_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Salt flats in Badwater Basin, Death Valley National Park, California, USA","Copyright":"© Jim Patterson/TANDEM Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260211_BadwaterFlats\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Death+Valley+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260211_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260211_BadwaterFlats"},"Ssd":"20260211","Name":"BadwaterFlats","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9539566313","FullDateString":"11. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Just southwest of Ibiza, Spain, lie the uninhabited islets of Es Vedrà and Es Vedranell. Part of a protected nature reserve, these dramatic rock formations are admired for their ecological value and visual impact. Es Vedrà rises around 400 metres straight from the sea, its sheer limestone cliffs resembling a mountain range. Nearby, the jagged outline of Es Vedranell has earned it the nickname 'sleeping dragon,' appearing to guard its larger sibling.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.IbizaIslets_ROW9500187441_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.IbizaIslets_ROW9500187441_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Islets of Es Vedrà and Es Vedranell, Ibiza, Spain","Copyright":"© L. Apolli/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260210_IbizaIslets\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Es+Vedra+Ibiza&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260210_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260210_IbizaIslets"},"Ssd":"20260210","Name":"IbizaIslets","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9500187441","FullDateString":"10. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The leopard cat is a small wild cat found across South, Southeast and East Asia. Similar in size to a house cat but longer-legged and slenderer, it generally measures 38–66 centimetres long, with a tail about 17–31 centimetres. Depending on the region, adults weigh roughly 0.55–7 kilograms. Their appearance varies widely: southern individuals tend to have warm golden coats, while those farther north often have pale grey fur that thickens for winter.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LeopardCat_ROW9470593052_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LeopardCat_ROW9470593052_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Amur leopard cat, Russia","Copyright":"© Valeriy Maleev/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260209_LeopardCat\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Leopard+cat&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260209_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260209_LeopardCat"},"Ssd":"20260209","Name":"LeopardCat","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9470593052","FullDateString":"9. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The island of Corfu, Greece, meets you at night with a quiet kind of intensity: stone facades catching warm lamplight, fortress walls rising in sharp outline and narrow lanes unfolding like a lived-in labyrinth. The Old Town doesn't just look historic—it feels inhabited, shaped by centuries of shifting cultures and the slow rhythm of island life after dark.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CorfuGreece_ROW8621582269_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CorfuGreece_ROW8621582269_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Corfu, Greece","Copyright":"© whitewizzard/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260208_CorfuGreece\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Corfu+Greece&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260208_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260208_CorfuGreece"},"Ssd":"20260208","Name":"CorfuGreece","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8621582269","FullDateString":"8. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Salar de Uyuni in Bolivia doesn't ease you in—it erupts into view like a horizon made of light. It's the world's largest salt flat, stretching across more than 10,400 square kilometres at nearly 3,658 metres above sea level. The landscape dramatically shifts with the seasons: when the rain arrives, the surface floods just enough to become an enormous mirror, so perfectly reflective that sky and ground melt into a single glowing plane.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SalarUyuni_ROW9588613912_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SalarUyuni_ROW9588613912_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Salar de Uyuni salt flats in Bolivia","Copyright":"© Abstract Aerial Art/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260207_SalarUyuni\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Salar+de+Uyuni+Bolivia&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260207_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260207_SalarUyuni"},"Ssd":"20260207","Name":"SalarUyuni","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9588613912","FullDateString":"7. Feb rrrr"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Yosemite National Park in California, United States, is renowned for its granite walls, dramatic waterfalls and striking light, all of which have inspired generations of artists. One of its most intriguing sights is the Firefall, a term that refers to two distinct events in the park's history. For decades, visitors gathered at Glacier Point to watch an artificial Firefall, in which embers were pushed off the cliff in a glowing stream of fire.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.AdamsFirefall_ROW1469118992_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.AdamsFirefall_ROW1469118992_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Horsetail Fall in Yosemite National Park, California, United States","Copyright":"© Jorge Villalba/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260220_AdamsFirefall\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Horsetail+Fall+Yosemite+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260220_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260220_AdamsFirefall"},"Ssd":"20260220","Name":"AdamsFirefall","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1469118992","FullDateString":"20. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Dragon's Eye sounds like something pulled from legend, and standing on Norway's Uttakleiv Beach in the Lofoten Islands, it's easy to see why. The formation, carved into ancient rock and framed by sand and sea, looks uncannily alive, as though the land itself is watching you. Shaped over thousands of years by ice and water, it has become one of the region's most captivating sights.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DragonsEyeRock_ROW1212085075_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DragonsEyeRock_ROW1212085075_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"The Dragon's Eye rock formation at Uttakleiv Beach, Norway","Copyright":"© reisegraf/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260219_DragonsEyeRock\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Uttakleiv+Beach+Norway&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260219_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260219_DragonsEyeRock"},"Ssd":"20260219","Name":"DragonsEyeRock","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1212085075","FullDateString":"19. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"This species missed the domestication memo and kept going on its own terms. Say hello to Przewalski's horse, considered the last truly wild horse on Earth. Once widespread across Central Asia, it disappeared from the wild in the 1960s after decades of hunting, habitat loss and competition with livestock. Its survival depended on an unlikely lifeline: a small number of individuals captured by early 20th‑century collectors, which became the foundation of all modern Przewalski's horses.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PrzewalskisHorse_ROW1038206758_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PrzewalskisHorse_ROW1038206758_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Przewalski's horses","Copyright":"© Nemyrivskyi Viacheslav/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260218_PrzewalskisHorse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Przewalskis+horse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260218_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260218_PrzewalskisHorse"},"Ssd":"20260218","Name":"PrzewalskisHorse","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1038206758","FullDateString":"18. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Ochagavía in Spain offers one of Navarre's most evocative winter scenes. This village of just over 480 residents, located in the Salazar Valley, 85 kilometres from Pamplona, stands out for its traditional architecture, with stone houses, steeply pitched roofs and a medieval bridge over the Anduña River that looks straight out of a postcard.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Navarra_ROW0874580487_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Navarra_ROW0874580487_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Ochagavía, Navarre, Spain","Copyright":"© PhotosTime/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260217_Navarra\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Ochagavia&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260217_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260217_Navarra"},"Ssd":"20260217","Name":"Navarra","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0874580487","FullDateString":"17. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Banff in Alberta, Canada, didn't grow quietly. It arrived with railways, hot springs and a vision: to protect places of rare beauty. In 1883, railway workers stumbled upon warm mineral water bubbling from Sulphur Mountain—an unlikely surprise in the cold sweep of the Rockies. The discovery drew attention quickly. By 1885, the surrounding land has been set aside as a protected reserve. What did that lead to? The beginnings of Banff National Park, Canada's first, and a blueprint the country would return to again and again.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BanffWinter_ROW0592236098_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BanffWinter_ROW0592236098_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Banff, Alberta, Canada","Copyright":"© Herbert Rong/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260216_BanffWinter\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Banff+town&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260216_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260216_BanffWinter"},"Ssd":"20260216","Name":"BanffWinter","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0592236098","FullDateString":"16. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Humpback whales are easily recognisable by their long pectoral fins and are known for their complex songs associated with breeding behaviour. Their predictable migrations bring them close to shore, turning them into both a cultural marker of the season and a focal point for early conservation efforts.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.MontereyHumpbacks_ROW0446556209_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.MontereyHumpbacks_ROW0446556209_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Humpback whales in Monterey Bay, California, USA","Copyright":"© Kiliii Fish/Cavan Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260215_MontereyHumpbacks\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Humpback+whales&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260215_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260215_MontereyHumpbacks"},"Ssd":"20260215","Name":"MontereyHumpbacks","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0446556209","FullDateString":"15. Feb rrrr"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At first glance, it looks like a love story that went a little too far. Pink hearts dangle from curved stems, each with a tiny white drop at the tip, as if the plant is mid-sigh. Meet the bleeding heart—proof that flowers can be dramatic without saying a word. Formally known as Dicentra spectabilis, it is a spring-flowering perennial native to eastern Asia. It can grow up to 60 centimetres tall and spread to nearly 75 centimetres wide, creating a graceful, almost poetic display.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ValentineHearts_ROW0216813332_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ValentineHearts_ROW0216813332_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Bleeding hearts","Copyright":"© Dorene Hookey/Cavan Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260214_ValentineHearts\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Bleeding+hearts&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260214_0800\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260214_ValentineHearts"},"Ssd":"20260214","Name":"ValentineHearts","Market":"ROW","Hash":"0216813332","FullDateString":"14. Feb rrrr"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCR